---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const wpoBody = `
  

  <!-- ============ SECTION 0: HERO ============ -->
  <header class="hero hero--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="hero-grid">
        <div class="hero-text">
          <div class="hero-eyebrow eyebrow">Wellness Practice Owner Mortgages</div>
          <h1 class="display-1">Mortgages for Wellness Practice Owners</h1>
          <p class="lead hero-subtitle">A lender who reads multi-entity S-corp distributions, med-spa procedure revenue, subscription membership recurring income, medical director supervision arrangements, and SBA expansion financing as one income picture. Working wellness practice owners &mdash; med-spa proprietors, IV therapy clinics, hormone optimization centers, regenerative medicine practices, weight loss centers, men&rsquo;s health clinics, integrative medicine clinics, peptide therapy practices &mdash; carry the most complex multi-entity income files in the wellness sector. A single year can include <strong>W-2 reasonable compensation from a primary S-corp ($120K&ndash;$220K), K-1 distributions from primary and each satellite-location entity each running $200K&ndash;$700K, med-spa procedure revenue from injectables and laser treatments, subscription membership recurring revenue ($150&ndash;$500/month per member at 200&ndash;1,000 active members), product retail revenue (skincare, supplements, peptides), MD or NP medical director supervision payments structured as employment or contractor relationships, equipment depreciation under IRC Section 179 on aesthetic lasers ($60K&ndash;$200K each), IV pumps, body sculpting devices, and SBA 7(a) or 504 financing for new satellite locations</strong>. Each location often operates as its own S-corp or LLC entity with the practice owner holding majority ownership. Generalist lenders default to the primary entity W-2 and miss the K-1s from satellite entities entirely. We aggregate the full picture.</p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call" class="btn btn-primary btn-large">Talk to Our Team</a>
            <a href="#income-methods" class="btn btn-secondary btn-large">See how multi-entity qualifying works</a>
          </div>
          <div class="hero-trust">
            <span class="trust-dot"></span>
            <span>Broker NMLS #1072866</span>
            <span>&middot;</span>
            <span>Specialist in multi-entity S-corp, med-spa expansion, membership recurring revenue, &amp; multi-location wellness practice owner mortgages</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="hero-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/3997992/pexels-photo-3997992.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1200" alt="Modern wellness practice and med-spa treatment center" width="1200" height="1500" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1200x1500/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Wellness+Owners';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- ============ STATS BAR ============ -->
  <section class="stats stats--with-image">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="stats-bar-grid">
        <div class="stats-grid">
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">$15B+</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Annual U.S. med-spa industry revenue per AmSpa State of the Industry research (growing 10&ndash;15% annually)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">10,000+</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Med-spa locations operating in the U.S., majority single-location independent practices owned by wellness practice operators</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">B3-3.4-02</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Fannie Mae rule allowing multi-entity K-1 aggregation across satellite-location S-corps</div>
          </div>
          <div class="stat">
            <div class="stat-num">2-4</div>
            <div class="stat-label">Typical satellite locations for mature wellness practice owners (each often separate S-corp or LLC)</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <figure class="stats-bar-image">
          <img src="https://images.pexels.com/photos/3997989/pexels-photo-3997989.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1000" alt="Modern wellness clinic interior with treatment equipment" width="1000" height="750" loading="lazy" onerror="this.onerror=null;this.src='https://placehold.co/1000x750/0A0E1A/E8EEFF/png?text=Wellness';">
        </figure>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ LEDE ============ -->
  <section class="lede-section lede-section--with-image">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <p class="lede">Stairway Mortgage qualifies wellness practice owners on the full income picture &mdash; <strong>S-corp W-2 reasonable compensation from primary entity plus K-1 distributions from primary AND each satellite-location entity under Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02 multi-entity aggregation, med-spa procedure revenue from injectables (Botox, dermal fillers, Sculptra, PDO threads), laser treatments (IPL, CO2, Q-switched, Nd:YAG, diode), body sculpting (CoolSculpting, EmSculpt, Morpheus8), microneedling, and IV therapy flowing through Schedule C or 1120-S gross revenue, subscription membership recurring revenue documented through merchant processor reports, product retail revenue from medical-grade skincare and supplements, MD or NP medical director supervision arrangements structured as employment or contractor relationships depending on state board requirements, Schedule C cash-flow analysis with Form 1084 addbacks for IRC Section 167 equipment depreciation on aesthetic lasers and treatment devices and Section 179 immediate equipment expensing, and SBA 7(a) and 504 expansion financing coordination for new satellite locations</strong>. A first-location wellness practice owner with $480K annual practice revenue, a mature single-location med-spa owner with established membership program, a multi-location wellness brand owner with 3 satellite med-spas each as separate S-corp, a hormone optimization clinic with employed MD medical director, and an established wellness practice owner mid-acquisition of a competitor&rsquo;s practice through SBA 7(a) each get qualified using methods that fit their actual structure. We pick the right door before we quote. Or skip ahead: browse <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">every loan program</a>, run numbers on <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">100+ mortgage calculators</a>, or check <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/current-rates/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">today&apos;s rates</a>. For the parent hub and other dental and wellness paths, see our <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/dental-wellness-professionals/" style="color: var(--blue); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px;">dental and wellness professionals mortgage hub</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #1: KEY FACTS ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 760px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">01 &middot; Wellness practice owner mortgage at a glance</div>
        <h2>Key facts every wellness practice owner should know before applying for a mortgage.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="key-facts-grid">
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">Multi-entity</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.7-01/analyzing-partnership-returns-partnership-or-llc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, multiple K-1s from sister S-corps (typical when wellness practice owners run satellite locations each as separate entity) aggregate into a single qualifying income figure. Each entity needs its own 2-year 1120-S history. Generalist lenders see one entity and miss the rest.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">AmSpa</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">The <a href="https://www.americanmedspa.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">American Med Spa Association (AmSpa)</a> is the primary trade association for the U.S. med-spa industry. AmSpa State of the Industry research documents the $15B+ U.S. med-spa market with 10&ndash;15% annual growth, providing industry context for underwriting wellness practice income patterns.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">MD/NP supervision</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">State medical board requirements vary substantially for medical-procedure supervision in wellness practices. Some states require physician (MD/DO) supervision; others allow nurse practitioner (NP) or physician assistant (PA) supervision. <a href="https://www.fsmb.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FSMB</a> tracks state-by-state requirements. The supervision arrangement (employed vs IC) affects entity structure and qualifying.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="key-fact-card">
          <div class="key-fact-num">SBA expansion</div>
          <p class="key-fact-body">Multi-location wellness practice expansion typically finances through <a href="https://www.sba.gov/funding-programs/loans/7a-loans" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SBA 7(a)</a> working capital and equipment loans (up to $5M) or <a href="https://www.sba.gov/funding-programs/loans/504-loans" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SBA 504</a> real estate loans. We sequence personal mortgages relative to satellite expansion timing.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #2: ROLE-STAGE SOLUTIONS ============ -->
  <section class="professions-section section-tinted">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">02 &middot; Where you are in your wellness practice ownership journey</div>
        <h2>Wellness practice owner mortgage solutions for every career stage.</h2>
        <p>Each stage of wellness practice ownership has its own qualifying logic. A first-location med-spa owner in Years 2-3 of practice ownership has a different mortgage path than a multi-location wellness brand owner with 3 satellite S-corps and an employed MD medical director, or a wellness practice owner mid-acquisition of a competitor&rsquo;s practice through SBA 7(a) financing.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="professions-grid">

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">01</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">First-location owner (Years 1&ndash;3)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Just opened first wellness practice or med-spa location. Building patient base, equipment investment heavy, possibly still drawing income from prior W-2 employment alongside practice."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual practice revenue $250K&ndash;$600K building toward stability</li>
            <li>Heavy Section 179 equipment expensing in early years</li>
            <li>May still have W-2 income from prior career transitioning out</li>
            <li>Schedule C self-employed with Form 1084 addbacks OR Bank-statement Non-QM</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See first-location mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">02</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Single-location mature owner (Years 3&ndash;7)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established single-location practice. Membership program operating with 200&ndash;600 active members. Considering S-corp election. Equipment investment stabilizing."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual practice revenue $500K&ndash;$1.5M</li>
            <li>S-corp election typically appropriate at this scale</li>
            <li>Membership recurring revenue providing income stability</li>
            <li>S-Corp Self-Employed Conventional with B3-3.4-02</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See single-location mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">03</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Multi-location expansion (2-4 locations)</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Successfully expanded to 2-4 satellite locations. Each often separate S-corp or LLC. Multi-entity K-1 aggregation becomes the qualifying default."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $600K&ndash;$1.8M through multi-entity K-1 distributions</li>
            <li>Multi-entity B3-3.4-02 aggregation across satellite location entities</li>
            <li>SBA 7(a)/504 coordination for additional satellite expansion</li>
            <li>Conventional jumbo or super-jumbo with multi-entity documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See multi-location mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">04</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Multi-location with employed medical director</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established multi-location practice with employed MD or NP medical director providing supervision per state board requirements. Practice scale typically $2M+ revenue."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $800K&ndash;$2.5M through multi-entity ownership</li>
            <li>Medical director arrangement structured as W-2 employment or 1099 IC</li>
            <li>State board compliance documentation supports practice income stability</li>
            <li>Super-jumbo S-corp Conventional or asset-depletion Non-QM</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See multi-location w/ MD mechanics</span>
        </a>

        <a class="profession-card" href="#income-methods">
          <div class="profession-num">05</div>
          <h3 class="profession-title">Multi-provider chain / wellness brand</h3>
          <p class="profession-tag">"Established wellness brand operating 5+ locations with multiple employed and contractor practitioners. Possibly PE-backed or independent multi-location chain."</p>
          <ul class="profession-points">
            <li>Annual income $1M&ndash;$5M+ through multi-entity ownership and brand</li>
            <li>Multiple K-1s from separate location entities under B3-3.4-02</li>
            <li>Asset-depletion against accumulated brand and reserves</li>
            <li>Super-jumbo conventional or asset-depletion Non-QM at scale</li>
          </ul>
          <span class="profession-link">See multi-provider chain mechanics</span>
        </a>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #3: INCOME CALCULATION METHODS ============ -->
  <section class="section" id="income-methods">
    <div class="container-narrow">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div class="eyebrow">03 &middot; The qualification mechanics</div>
        <h2>How we calculate qualifying income for your wellness practice owner mortgage.</h2>
        <p>Four methods cover almost every wellness practice owner file we&rsquo;ve closed. The right method depends on your career stage, whether you operate single-location vs multi-location, the role of subscription membership recurring revenue, and how medical director supervision arrangements are structured.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Method 1 &mdash; Multi-entity S-corp aggregation (the satellite-location default)</h3>
      <p>For wellness practice owners operating multiple S-corps (one per satellite location) or a parent S-corp with subsidiary entities. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.7-01/analyzing-partnership-returns-partnership-or-llc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, qualifying income aggregates: (1) W-2 reasonable compensation paid by the primary S-corp ($120K&ndash;$220K typical for wellness practice owners), plus (2) K-1 distributions from each entity supported by 2-year <a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1120-s" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Form 1120-S</a> history, plus (3) Form 1084 addbacks at the consolidated practice level for documented non-cash expenses (depreciation on aesthetic lasers, IV pumps, body sculpting devices, treatment chairs; Section 179 expensing on equipment-acquisition years; amortization on practice goodwill from acquisitions). The owner must hold sufficient ownership in each entity to claim the K-1 income.</p>

      <h3>Method 2 &mdash; S-corp self-employed with W-2 + K-1 (the single-location path)</h3>
      <p>For wellness practice owners with single mature location operating as S-corp. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.7-01/analyzing-partnership-returns-partnership-or-llc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, qualifying income combines W-2 reasonable compensation plus K-1 distributions with 2-year history. Form 1084 addbacks recover equipment depreciation under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/167" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 167</a> and Section 179 expensing under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/179" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 179</a>. Wellness practices are exceptionally equipment-heavy: aesthetic lasers ($60K&ndash;$200K each), body sculpting devices ($80K&ndash;$200K), IV pumps and infusion equipment, hormone testing equipment. Equipment-acquisition years can suppress taxable income by $200K+ at the entity level &mdash; Form 1084 systematically recovers this.</p>

      <h3>Method 3 &mdash; Bank-statement Non-QM (the membership recurring revenue path)</h3>
      <p>For wellness practice owners with strong membership recurring revenue programs whose Schedule C or 1120-S net profit aggressively suppresses below actual practice cash generation due to heavy equipment expensing or expansion investment. Under <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/43/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CFPB Reg Z&rsquo;s Ability-to-Repay rule</a>, non-QM bank-statement programs qualify based on 12 or 24 months of personal or business bank deposits at 50&ndash;75% counting. Particularly useful for med-spas with $200&ndash;$500/month membership programs at 300+ active members generating $1M+ of predictable monthly deposits that tax returns may understate due to legitimate expensing.</p>

      <h3>Method 4 &mdash; Asset-depletion Non-QM (the mature scale path)</h3>
      <p>For mature multi-location wellness practice owners with significant accumulated reserves, retained earnings across multiple entities, and complex income patterns that may include partnership distributions, equipment finance lease arrangements, and product retail revenue. Asset-depletion Non-QM amortizes liquid assets over 360 months as implied income, providing an alternative qualifying path for owners whose current-year income is variable due to expansion investment or whose accumulated wealth substantially exceeds current-year income capacity. Often pairs with multi-entity B3-3.4-02 analysis as a complement.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #4: DARK SECTION ============ -->
  <section class="per-diem-section per-diem-section--bg qualifying--bg section-dark" style="background-image: url('https://images.pexels.com/photos/3997992/pexels-photo-3997992.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&w=1800');">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="max-width: 760px;">
        <div class="eyebrow eyebrow-light">04 &middot; What generalist underwriting misses</div>
        <h2 style="color: var(--paper);">The income most lenders refuse to count on a wellness practice owner file.</h2>
        <p style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.78);">Six income streams that show up consistently on working wellness practice owner files and that generalist lenders typically either ignore, mis-categorize, or refuse to apply correctly. Each one is documentable; the lender just has to read the multi-entity practice financials, membership processor reports, equipment finance schedules, and supervision arrangements properly.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="dark-grid">
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">A</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Multi-entity K-1 aggregation across satellite locations</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Wellness practice owners with 2-5 satellite locations commonly run each as a separate S-corp or LLC with its own EIN, books, and K-1. The owner holds majority ownership across all entities. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.7-01/analyzing-partnership-returns-partnership-or-llc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, K-1 distributions from each entity aggregate as qualifying income with 2-year 1120-S history per entity. Generalist lenders default to the primary entity W-2 and miss the satellite K-1s entirely. Result: $400K&ndash;$1.5M of qualifying income disappears.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">B</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Med-spa procedure revenue (injectables, lasers, body sculpting)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Med-spa revenue mix typically includes injectables (Botox, Dysport, Xeomin, dermal fillers, Sculptra, PDO threads), laser treatments (IPL, CO2 ablative/non-ablative, Q-switched, Nd:YAG, diode hair removal), body sculpting (CoolSculpting, EmSculpt, Morpheus8 radiofrequency, EmTone), microneedling, chemical peels, and IV therapy. Per <a href="https://www.americanmedspa.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">AmSpa</a> data, injectables typically represent 40&ndash;55% of med-spa revenue. All flows through Schedule C or 1120-S gross revenue as ordinary practice income with 2-year history under standard self-employment treatment.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">C</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Subscription/membership recurring revenue</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Wellness practice membership programs ($150&ndash;$500/month per member, bundling monthly aesthetic treatments, IV therapy, skincare credits) generate predictable recurring revenue. At 300&ndash;1,000 active members, this stream alone produces $540K&ndash;$3M annually. Revenue flows through Schedule C or 1120-S as practice gross revenue, documented through merchant processor reports (Stripe, Square, dedicated practice management platforms). Bank-statement Non-QM captures membership cash flow particularly cleanly.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">D</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">MD/NP medical director supervision arrangements</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">State medical board requirements vary substantially for wellness practice medical procedure supervision. Some states require physician (MD/DO) supervision; others allow nurse practitioner (NP) or physician assistant (PA) supervision. The wellness practice owner&rsquo;s relationship with the medical director may be W-2 employment (medical director on payroll) or 1099 IC (contracted supervision per <a href="https://www.fsmb.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">FSMB</a> state guidance). The supervision arrangement affects entity structure but does not affect the wellness practice owner&rsquo;s qualifying income directly &mdash; the practice revenue continues to flow through the owner&rsquo;s S-corp.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">E</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Section 179 equipment expensing across multi-entity structure</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Wellness practice equipment is exceptionally capital-intensive: aesthetic lasers ($60K&ndash;$200K each, often 3-5 per location), body sculpting devices ($80K&ndash;$200K), IV pumps and infusion equipment, hormone testing devices, microneedling RF platforms, CO2 surgical lasers. Under <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/179" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--blue-soft);">IRC Section 179</a>, equipment can be immediately expensed up to $1.16M (2024 indexed) per year per entity. For wellness practice owners with multi-entity structures, Section 179 expensing can suppress taxable income across multiple sister entities simultaneously. Form 1084 cash-flow analysis adds these back at each entity level.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="dark-card">
          <div class="dark-num">F</div>
          <h3 class="dark-card-title" style="color: var(--paper);">Product retail revenue (skincare, supplements, peptides)</h3>
          <p class="dark-card-body" style="color: rgba(250,250,247,0.72);">Mature wellness practices commonly carry product retail revenue from medical-grade skincare lines (SkinCeuticals, Obagi, ZO Skin Health, Alastin, Skinbetter), supplements, peptide therapy products, and hormone replacement therapy compounds (when MD/NP supervised). Product retail typically represents 8&ndash;15% of mature practice revenue with strong margins. Revenue flows through Schedule C or 1120-S gross revenue with cost-of-goods reducing to net profit. Bank-statement Non-QM particularly captures product retail revenue where Schedule C net profit obscures the gross cash flow.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ H2 #5: LOAN PROGRAM MATRIX ============ -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="section-header" style="text-align: center; max-width: 720px; margin: 0 auto;">
        <div class="eyebrow">05 &middot; Match the program to your wellness practice scale</div>
        <h2>Which loan program fits your wellness practice owner mortgage situation.</h2>
        <p>Seven loan-program categories cover essentially every wellness practice owner file we&rsquo;ve closed. The mix tilts toward Multi-Entity S-Corp Conventional (for multi-location wellness brand owners) and S-Corp Self-Employed Conventional with Form 1084 addbacks (for single-location mature owners).</p>
      </div>
      <div class="loan-program-grid">

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Multi-Entity S-Corp Conventional</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Wellness practice owners with 2-5 satellite locations</li>
            <li>Aggregated K-1 distributions across entities under B3-3.4-02</li>
            <li>2-year 1120-S per entity with ownership documentation</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Multi-location owner</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">S-Corp Self-Employed Conventional</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Single-location mature wellness practice with S-corp election</li>
            <li>W-2 reasonable comp + K-1 distributions under B3-3.4-02</li>
            <li>Form 1084 addbacks for equipment depreciation and Section 179</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Single-location owner</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Bank-Statement Non-QM</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Membership-heavy practices with strong recurring revenue</li>
            <li>12 or 24 months of business deposits at 50&ndash;75% counting</li>
            <li>Captures cash flow that Schedule C suppresses through expensing</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="loan-program-tag">Best for: Membership-heavy practice</div>
        </div>

        <div class="loan-program-card">
          <h3 class="loan-program-name">Asset-Depletion Non-QM</h3>
          <ul class="loan-program-points">
            <li>Mature wellness practice owners with accumulated reserves</li>
            <li>Liquid assets amortized over 360 months as implied income</li>
            <li>Useful during expansion years when current income variable</li>
          </ul>
