        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">01</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I run 3 med-spa locations as separate S-corps. How do they aggregate for qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.7-01/analyzing-partnership-returns-partnership-or-llc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, K-1 distributions from multiple S-corps aggregate as qualifying income when you hold sufficient ownership in each entity and each has 2-year 1120-S history. We pull <a href="https://www.irs.gov/forms-pubs/about-form-1120-s" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Form 1120-S</a> per entity, all Schedule K-1s, and your personal 1040, document the ownership percentages and intercompany cash flows, and qualify you on the consolidated total.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">02</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My med-spa has $124K/month in membership revenue. Does that count differently?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Membership recurring revenue flows through Schedule C or 1120-S gross revenue as ordinary practice income. The qualifying treatment is the same as other practice revenue under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.5-01/underwriting-factors-and-documentation-self-employed-borrower" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.3-02</a> or B3-3.4-02 depending on entity structure. The advantage of strong membership: it documents predictable recurring cash flow that bank-statement Non-QM captures particularly cleanly, and it reduces business risk in the underwriter&rsquo;s assessment.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">03</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I have an employed MD medical director on payroll. How does that affect my qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">The MD&rsquo;s W-2 salary is a practice operating expense, not your personal income or expense. It reduces practice net profit before flowing to your K-1, but it&rsquo;s a legitimate ordinary expense. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.7-01/analyzing-partnership-returns-partnership-or-llc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a>, the 2-year history of net income after the MD&rsquo;s salary is the qualifying base. State board <a href="https://www.fsmb.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FSMB</a> compliance documentation supports practice operational legitimacy.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">04</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My equipment finance debt shows on my personal credit. Does that hurt qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">It depends on the structure. If the equipment finance is personally guaranteed and shows on personal credit, the payment counts in personal DTI calculation. However, equipment finance payments for legitimate business equipment can often be excluded from DTI if the entity is making the payments through its own banking. We document the entity-paid history to support exclusion. If equipment finance is structured at the entity level without personal guarantee, it doesn&rsquo;t affect personal DTI.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">05</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My Section 179 equipment expensing suppresses one year&rsquo;s income substantially. What happens?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Form 1084 cash-flow analysis adds back <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/26/179" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 179</a> expensing as a non-cash deduction. For wellness practices with $200K&ndash;$400K of equipment acquired in a single year, Section 179 can suppress taxable income by similar amounts. Form 1084 systematically restores this. We coordinate with your practice CPA to identify all addbacks at each entity level.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">06</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m expanding to a 4th location. Should I close the personal mortgage before or after the SBA?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Generally close the personal mortgage BEFORE the new SBA loan funds. Each satellite expansion adds new business debt that may appear on personal credit (typical for first-100% guaranteed SBA loans) and reshapes income temporarily as the new location ramps. The cleanest sequence: close the personal mortgage using stable existing 3-entity multi-K-1 income, then close the 4th satellite SBA financing 60-180 days later.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">07</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My practice generates product retail revenue from skincare and supplements. Does that count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes &mdash; product retail revenue flows through Schedule C or 1120-S gross revenue as ordinary practice income with 2-year history qualifying under standard self-employment treatment. Medical-grade skincare lines, supplements, peptide products, and HRT compounds all count when documented. We work with merchant processor reports and inventory records to document the product retail revenue stream.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">08</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What documentation do I need for multi-entity qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For each entity: two years of Form 1120-S corporate returns with Schedule K-1s, Schedule L showing retained earnings, and confirmation of your ownership percentage. Plus your personal 1040 with all schedules for the same two years. Plus 60 days of personal and business bank statements across all entities. Plus medical director arrangement documentation (W-2 or 1099) and state board compliance per <a href="https://www.fsmb.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FSMB</a> if applicable. We coordinate the documentation pull with your practice CPA upfront.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">09</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My newest location is only 14 months old. Can the K-1 still count?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">For conventional S-corp qualifying under B3-3.4-02, typically you need 2 years of 1120-S history per entity. Workarounds: (1) qualify primarily on the established entities with 2+ year history, treating the newest as supplementary supporting information; (2) bank-statement Non-QM looking at the new entity&rsquo;s business deposits; (3) wait the additional months. We model the trade-offs.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">10</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are mortgage rates higher for wellness practice owners?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Base conventional rates are the same for wellness practice owners as for any other borrower at the same credit profile. Non-QM bank-statement programs carry a 0.5&ndash;1.0% rate premium because of looser documentation. For multi-location owners with proper B3-3.4-02 multi-entity documentation, conventional jumbo at standard rates is achievable even at $3M+ loan amounts.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">11</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Do my satellite locations need to be in the same state for K-1s to aggregate?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No. Federal mortgage qualifying under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.7-01/analyzing-partnership-returns-partnership-or-llc" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-3.4-02</a> aggregates K-1 distributions from S-corps regardless of state of incorporation, as long as you hold sufficient ownership and each has 2-year 1120-S federal tax history. State-level licensing and supervision rules per <a href="https://www.fsmb.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FSMB</a> are separate matters. Multi-state wellness practice owners qualify on the consolidated federal picture.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">12</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">I&rsquo;m acquiring a competitor&rsquo;s wellness practice. How does that timing work?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Wellness practice acquisitions typically run $1M&ndash;$5M+ depending on revenue and goodwill. <a href="https://www.sba.gov/funding-programs/loans/7a-loans" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">SBA 7(a)</a> financing up to $5M is the norm. We sequence the personal mortgage either BEFORE the SBA closes (using stable existing multi-entity income) or AFTER the acquired practice integrates and stabilizes 60-180 days later (using consolidated owner economics with the new entity).</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">13</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can I qualify on bank-statement Non-QM if my Schedule C/1120-S looks lower than actual cash flow?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes. Under <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/43/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CFPB Reg Z Ability-to-Repay</a>, non-QM bank-statement programs qualify based on 12 or 24 months of business deposits at 50&ndash;75% counting. Particularly useful when membership recurring revenue plus equipment-heavy Section 179 expensing creates a substantial gap between practice deposits and tax-return net profit. Rate is 0.5&ndash;1.0% higher than conforming but qualifying capacity often substantially larger.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">14</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My S-corp has retained earnings across multiple entities. Are those usable as reserves?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Generally yes if accessible. S-corp retained earnings in each entity&rsquo;s business accounts count as reserves if you have the ability to distribute them. Documented via Schedule L (balance sheet) on each 1120-S. For mature multi-location wellness practice owners, aggregated retained earnings across all entities often represent significant reserve strength supporting super-jumbo qualifying.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">15</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does the IRS Section 199A QBI deduction affect me?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Wellness practice ownership involving medical procedures (injectables, lasers, IV therapy under MD/NP supervision) generally falls within the Specified Service Trade or Business (SSTB) classification under <a href="https://www.irs.gov/newsroom/qualified-business-income-deduction" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">IRC Section 199A</a>. Established wellness practice owners typically sit ABOVE the phase-out ($191,950-$241,950 for single filers 2024 indexed) where SSTB deduction zeroes out. The deduction&rsquo;s absence reduces the AGI line that some underwriters use for affordability. We coordinate with your CPA to document the right numbers.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">16</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My practice received an acquisition offer from a PE-backed med-spa platform. How does that affect my mortgage timing?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Forward-visibility on a potential practice sale affects timing strategy. If you intend to close the personal mortgage BEFORE the sale, use current multi-entity income picture. If the sale closes first, you may transition to W-2 employment with the platform (post-sale earnout typically structured as W-2 + earnout payments) and qualifying becomes simpler. We coordinate with your M&amp;A advisor on personal mortgage timing relative to expected close.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">17</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Are there mortgage programs specifically for wellness practice owners or med-spa owners?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">No dedicated "wellness practice owner mortgage" product exists in mainstream lending. What matters more is finding a broker who understands multi-entity B3-3.4-02 K-1 aggregation across satellite locations, Form 1084 cash-flow analysis for equipment-heavy practices, bank-statement Non-QM for membership-recurring-revenue practices, SBA 7(a)/504 expansion financing coordination, and the state board supervision requirements documented by <a href="https://www.fsmb.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FSMB</a>.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">18</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My spouse is also involved in the practice. How does that affect qualifying?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">If your spouse holds ownership interest in the practice entities, the joint application aggregates both ownership percentages of K-1 distributions. If your spouse is W-2 employed by the practice (legitimate role, reasonable compensation), the W-2 income qualifies as standard B3-3.1-01 employment for the spouse. If your spouse holds outside W-2 employment, that income adds as standard co-borrower income.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">19</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My practice has product retail through Stripe and merchant processors. How is that documented?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Merchant processor monthly reports (Stripe, Square, Authorize.net, custom practice management platforms) document the product retail revenue stream. This income flows through Schedule C or 1120-S gross revenue line as practice sales. Under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-3.5-01/underwriting-factors-and-documentation-self-employed-borrower" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">B3-3.3-02</a> or B3-3.4-02 depending on entity, the merchant processor reports support practice gross revenue documentation alongside the tax returns.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">20</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">What about pharmacy or compounding relationships? Are those income streams?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Wellness practices with hormone replacement therapy programs typically partner with compounding pharmacies that supply bioidentical hormone preparations. The relationship is typically purchase-based (practice buys compound, marks up for patient charge) rather than commission-based. Revenue flows through Schedule C/1120-S gross revenue with cost-of-goods reducing to net. We work with the practice CPA to document the pharmacy relationship structure for the underwriter.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">21</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">My state requires MD supervision for laser procedures. How does that affect my entity structure?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">State board <a href="https://www.fsmb.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FSMB</a> supervision requirements affect operational structure but typically not your qualifying income directly. Your entity may include an employed MD or 1099 IC MD providing supervision. The MD compensation is a practice operating expense reducing net practice profit before your K-1 distribution. Documentation includes the MD agreement, state board compliance evidence, and the practice operational structure.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">22</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Can a co-borrower help me qualify if my practice is still in expansion mode?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Yes, significantly. Co-borrower files combine W-2s, 1099s, Schedule C, and S-corp distributions from both parties. For wellness practice owners in expansion years where practice income is variable due to Section 179 expensing and new-location ramping, a co-borrower with stable W-2 income often substantially helps qualifying ratios.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">23</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">How does my SBA loan for satellite expansion affect personal DTI?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">If the SBA loan is personally guaranteed (typical for first-100% guaranteed SBA loans) and the SBA payments hit personal credit, they appear in personal DTI. For entity-paid SBA debt with documented entity payment history, the debt can often be excluded from personal DTI. We document the SBA payment structure and entity payment history to support proper treatment under <a href="https://selling-guide.fanniemae.com/sel/b3-6-05/monthly-debt-obligations" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Fannie Mae B3-6-05</a>.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">24</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">When should I start the mortgage conversation relative to a home purchase?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Ideally 120-150 days before you intend to make an offer &mdash; longer than most other professional borrowers. Wellness practice owner files take longer because of multi-entity 1120-S review across each location, Form 1084 addbacks at the entity level for equipment depreciation and Section 179, medical director arrangement documentation, possible SBA expansion-financing sequencing, and merchant processor documentation for membership and product retail revenue. Starting early prevents close-of-escrow surprises.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-num">25</div>
          <div>
            <div class="faq-q">Why do generalist lenders refuse wellness practice owner files when there&rsquo;s clearly significant income?</div>
            <div class="faq-a">Three reasons: (1) Multi-entity K-1 aggregation under B3-3.4-02 across satellite locations is unfamiliar to generalist lenders who default to single-entity W-2 borrowers; (2) heavy Section 179 equipment expensing on aesthetic lasers and devices suppresses tax-return net profit, requiring Form 1084 to recover qualifying income; (3) the membership subscription recurring revenue model and product retail streams require deliberate documentation that generalist lenders don&rsquo;t know to request. The income is all there and verifiable &mdash; the file just needs a broker who reads multi-entity wellness practice structures correctly.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

